   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28591_1783_12_06_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>

               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworth's Town</placeName> <date when="1783-12-08">December the 6<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date><lb/>
               </dateline>  
               <note>6</note>
</opener>
                  <p> 
                     No indeed my sprightly Fanny I don't think you "a very<lb/>
                     saucy Girl" but a very good Physician and kind friend - I will not<lb/>
                     pay so <del>good</del> high a compliment to my own temper as to say that<lb/>
                     I heard your Sentence without Emotion or so bad a one to your<lb/>
                     Judgement <unclear>&amp;</unclear> to conceal the full Effect it had upon my Mind.<lb/>
                     But do me the justice to believe that I never for an instant<lb/>
                     <del>doubted</del> arraigned your Decision; ; in short I believe instead<lb/>
                     of <hi rend="underline">pressing</hi> my thoughts into fine Sentences I had better tell<lb/>
                     you the facts without any further preamble - first then<lb/>
                     know that the unfortunate scenes are devoted to the flames<lb/>
                     saving one which has been reserved for <add>a</add> more lingering though<lb/>
                     not less ignominious fate; being previously <unclear>streched </unclear>upon a<lb/>
                     catgut Rack it was bored through with a sharp instrument &amp;<lb/>
                     having a head to protect the fingers of the unfeeling Executionioner<lb/>
                     then clipt by slow degrees with a pair of Enormous Shears till<lb/>
                     at length after repeated Effort it was wrought into the pattern<lb/>
                     of a cap in which degraded form it for the present exists -<lb/>
                     Tyrant art thou satisfied ? - So much for the effect of your<lb/>
                     cruelty now for the honor <del>of <unclear></unclear></del> of your medical Skill<lb/>
                     I can safely swear that you have cured me of the <unclear>Manic</unclear> of<lb/>
                     Play Writing at least for the Winter Season, but you know such<lb/>
                     diseases when they attack the Body instead of the Mind usually<lb/>
                     return at Spring and fade so that I cannot depend upon a <choice><orig>radi<lb/>

                        <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28591_1783_12_06_page02.jpg"/>
                        
               -cal</orig><reg>radical</reg></choice> Cure; ; In case of a second Eruption I'm sure my good friend<lb/>
                     will Administer the same Medicines or more violent <choice><orig>one's</orig><reg>ones</reg></choice> if the<lb/>
                     disease should prove obstinate - Perhaps I am not quite <choice><orig>intelli<lb/>
                        -gible</orig><reg>intelligible</reg></choice>, but God forbid that for the sake of being so I should <choice><orig>tran-<lb/>
               -slate</orig><reg>translate</reg></choice> the french Word I have ventured to make use of .-<lb/>
                     What are you going to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Wimpole_ENK">Wimpole Street</placeName> again, I consider this<lb/>
               as a kind of second parting; and I shan't hear from you and you'll<lb/>
                     quite forget me! ! and I shall be all alone in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName>! ! your gay<lb/>
               entertaining companions will rival the <hi rend="underline">grave</hi> - <hi rend="underline">sedate</hi> - <hi rend="underline">young</hi><lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">lady</hi> <hi rend="underline">Alack and a well a day</hi>! ! what will become of her? -<lb/>
                     Oh that I could bribe <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FosbrX1">Fosbrooke</persName> to take my part &amp; keep me<lb/>
               in your Mind will you ever talk, will you ever think of your<lb/>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Edge'</persName>? let me drawers, let my bed, my stool any thing stand for<lb/>
                     me - How am I to praise <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FosbrX1"><unclear>Fossè</unclear></persName>, as we used to call her<lb/>
               perhaps she won't do as much for me, well then tell her she's<lb/>
               very ungrateful for that I thought her a very good natured<lb/>
               chearful, sprightly giddy Girl - Oh I have a thousand Questions<lb/> 
               to ask her, tell her that I beg she will write to me and tell<lb/>
                     me how she left all things, living &amp; being at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Derby_ENK"><unclear>Derby</unclear></placeName>, how all old<lb/>
                     School Mates do particularly <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BlakX1">Blakeway</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HodsX1">Hodson</persName>, how many<lb/>
                     <hi rend="underline">hundred</hi> Scrapes <persName ref="./Personography.xml#XxxxE2">Emmeline</persName> has been in since we parted<lb/>
               what party she is in &amp;c &amp;c - and pray ask her if I was a<lb/>
                     <hi rend="underline">grave</hi> <hi rend="underline">sedate</hi> <hi rend="underline">young</hi> <hi rend="underline">Lady</hi> at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LatifX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>.. <unclear>Latiffiere's</unclear></persName>; Has she forgot our<lb/>
                     leaping off the top Scaffold at the hazard of our own necks, of our<lb/>
                     noses at least, and our having the fools cap on for walking<lb/>
                     on the Rails of the Stairs going to the Drawing Room &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FordX1">Miss<lb/>
               
                     <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28591_1783_12_06_page03.jpg"/>
                     
               Ford</persName>'s popping out upon us and crying <hi rend="underline">So Ladies!</hi> and a thousand<lb/>
                     other pretty pranks she'll divert you with up in the Corner<lb/>
               by the fireplace where you and I have Chattered many a <choice><orig>live-<lb/>
                  long</orig><reg>livelong</reg></choice> hour - Au reste she can chatter as fast as either of us<lb/>
               and giggle faster, you'll like her pour passer le temps <unclear>vastly</unclear><lb/>
                     I think she is not unlike <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HxxxX2">Miss H.</persName> in person. - But you will<lb/>
               tell me all about her when you come to me again Oh and when<lb/>
                     will that be? ? Pray don't forget me to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#XxxxP1">Penelope</persName>; I hope she will<lb/>
                     sometimes think and make you think of me - Is <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CaveX1"><unclear>Cave</unclear></persName><lb/>
                     still at School? ? indeed I think just as you do of her - but<lb/>
               the next time you ask my opinion don't tell me your's<lb/>
                        first - what's become of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LushS1">Lushington</persName> and her <hi rend="underline">comment</hi><lb/>
                        <hi rend="underline">pouvez dire comme cela Mààm selle</hi>! Poor <persName ref="./Personography.xml#NimbX1">Nimbhard</persName>!<lb/>
                     If I live a thousand years I shall never forget her coming<lb/>
               up to me when I was perched up <del></del> in the middle of<lb/>
               the Room upon a high stool, when it was <hi rend="underline">Sin</hi> to approach<lb/>
                     and <hi rend="underline">Death</hi> to pity one she came up &amp; whispered <hi rend="underline">ne pleurez</hi><lb/>
                     <hi rend="underline">pas ma chere <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Edgeworth</persName></hi> there was more true goodness of heart<lb/>
                     &amp; friendship in that simple Sentence than I perhaps shall<lb/>
               often meet with from more sentimental friends, if ever<lb/>
               I meet her again I'll tell her so - Poor Girl! I do love<lb/>
               her for it - apropos what was my Crime, for to this hour<lb/>
                        I don't know, <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DxxxX3">M<hi rend="superscript">rs.</hi> D.</persName> thought I was laughing at her didn't<lb/>
                     she? I'm sure I was so innocent of any <hi rend="underline">wicked</hi> Intentions<lb/>
                     as the Child unborn God knows! pray tell me if I am ever<lb/>
               spoken of and how?- - -<lb/>
               You see I'm determined not to torment you with my Books<lb/>
               
                     <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28591_1783_12_06_page04.jpg"/>
                     
               and gravity any anymore - I hope you don't think my Dear Girl<lb/>
               that I meant what I said about <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">my Mother</persName> as any Reproach<lb/>
               or that I looked upon the sending of compliments as a necessary<lb/>
               Etiquette; no indeed what I said was merely from a wish<lb/>
               that you should feel interested for my family as I do for<lb/>
               your's - I long to see <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RobiX2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Robinson</persName>'s Verses -<lb/>
                     as for <unclear>Politico</unclear>, Mum's the word - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">my father</persName>'s to come home<lb/>
               tomorrow Oh joy and jubilee! - <lb/>
               How could you bestow six lines upon those wretched <choice><orig>flow-<lb/>
                  ers</orig><reg>flowers</reg></choice> which wer'nt worth six farthings -<lb/>
               As you were so kind to say <hi rend="underline">How I long for your answer</hi><lb/>
               I have prefered writing a speedy to a long one <choice><orig><hi rend="underline">parti-</hi><lb/>
                  <hi rend="underline">-cularly</hi></orig><reg>particularly</reg></choice> <hi rend="underline">as all the family are gone to Bed - So adieu</hi><lb/>
               my kind Friend and good Physician, preserve all<lb/>
               your sprightly freedom &amp; good goodnatured sincerity and<lb/>
               sometimes think of her who often thinks of you</p><lb/>
            <closer>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
               </closer>
                     <postscript>
                        <p>I beg my Respectful compliments to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RobiG1">L<hi rend="superscript">d.</hi></persName> and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RobiX2">Lady Robinson</persName><lb/>
                  not out of form - for I'm thoroughly convinced that a <choice><orig>mo-<lb/>
                     ther</orig><reg>mother</reg></choice> who has given such an Excellent and <hi rend="underline">successful</hi><lb/>
                  Education to her Daughter must be an amiable<lb/>
                  as well as sensible Woman - My love &amp; my <unclear>Direction</unclear><lb/>
                           to the <hi rend="underline">new</hi> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HartX1">Hartley</persName> - answer Quick as I have done<lb/>
                  In the dead of night no Mortal stirring!<lb/>
                  What shall I do! I can't for the life of me find y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. I <unclear></unclear> though I've<lb/>
                  your letter under my hand.- Had I best send this without one or<lb/>
                  not send it at all?- Pray don't be angry &amp; I'll look for it all day tomorrow</p><lb/>
                     </postscript> 
         </div>
      </body>
